# These represent a round-trip light time for range measurements
# by the NASA Deep Space Network to the Mars Reconaissance Orbiter spacecraft.
#
# Since range measurement errors are dominated by error in calibration of
# the signal delay through the tracking station prior to each tracking pass,
# there is effectively only one independent range point for each pass.
# This file therefore contains only one range point for each tracking pass.
#
# See P. Kuchynka et al.,
# Station-speciic errors in Mars ranging measurements,
# JPL IPN Progress report 42-190, 15 August 2012
# http://ipnpr/progress_report/42-190/190C.pdf
#
# The measured range to the spacecraft has been adjusted to the Mars system barycenter
# by an estimate of the spacecraft orbit derived from Doppler tracking.
# Users of these reduced data are requested to reference the paper
# A. S. Konopliv et al., Icarus volume 211, pages 401-428, 2011.
#
# A calibration for the tropospheric and ionospheric path delay
# at the DSN stations has been applied based on calibration
# data specific to the time of each measurement.
#
# No calibration or model for solar plasma has been applied.
# The measurements are all at X-band, with Earth-to-spacecraft signals sent
# at ~7.2GHz, and spacecraft-to-Earth signals sent at ~8.4 GHz.
#
# A calibration for the electronic delay in the spacecraft transponder
# has been applied to each measurement. Similarly a calibration for the
# DSN tracking station measured for each tracking pass has been applied.
# However, the electronic delay calibrations are not perfect. A constant correction
# to the spacecraft transponder delay is typically estimated for the data arc used.
# The DSN station delay calibration is typically accurate to seven nanoseconds.
#
# The DSN delay calibration error is common to all measurements in the tracking pass,
# so the errors are correlated. There is additional noise in each range measurement,
# due to the signal strength, which is typically about two nanoseconds.
# The station delay calibration accuray has been studied in a report available at
# http://ipnpr.jpl.nasa.gov/progress_report/42-190/190C.pdf
#
